metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #830
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.description:
Even you can't take a plane to another country now, you can always take the Choo Choo Train.

Drag the control bar on the lower left side, you can control the speed of the train as your wish.

[Mouse]
Drag the control bar: Speed of the train

[Keyboard]
[1] Hide the control bar
[2] Show the control bar
[s] Save in PNG

metadata.name: Celestial Objects #11
metadata.description:
Celestial Objects is a generative collection imagining planets and stars in the space, with light and shadows being key themes. 

The artwork is primarily rendered using hundreds of thousands of points (more than a million in some cases) to create different aspects of the output including the sky textures, shooting stars and shadows on the planets. 

Celestial Objects is coded in p5.js, and please note that it takes 5-15 seconds for each output to render.

Controls (in live view): 
Press [2] to render 2000x2000px image
Press [4] to render 4000x4000px image
Press [s] to save the current view (default window size or 2000px or 4000px image)

metadata.name: Other ways #140
metadata.description:
Inspired by Paul Klee’s painting « Highways and byways », « Other ways » propose to build your own and unique generative painting.

7 features, including 4 main styles, 8 color palettes, 5 different parameters of the generative process.


Please note that the preview image is more saturated than the real token due to fxhash GPU management.

In Open Live window, press « s » to save the current image.
To get a High Resolution Image : press « r » to change the resolution for high definition, the image will reload and you can then use « s » to save the image (you can change DP in the URL to  a greater value for an even larger resolution in case you want to print it big).
This project is dimensionless, the Preview and OpenLive images are the same.

This artwork was created using p5js and scribble.

TidallyDisruptedStar. Paris. Jan 2022.

metadata.name: Concrete #517
metadata.description:
640 unique sketches of imaginary walls, inspired by the work of Norwegian architect Erling Viksjø (1910–1971) and his artist collaborators. Viksjø designed the Government Quarter in Oslo and invited artists from different disciplines to help design the facades and interiors of the buildings.

Viksjø’s aim was to “soften” modernist architecture. He invented «Natural Concrete», a type of concrete that deliberately exposes the mixed-in stones on its surface to give it warmth and a human touch. In my work, I have similar ambitions—using code instead of concrete.

The different styles of the piece are inspired by, and dedicated to some of the artists who worked together with Viksjø: Jakob Weidemann (~2%), Carl Nesjar (~18%), Odd Tandberg (~30%), and Tore Haaland (~50%).

In live mode, press ‘S’ to save an image at current resolution or ‘P’ to save a high-resolution file at 6000×6000px (this might take a while depending on your hardware).

Original artwork by Andreas Rau · Made with p5.js & glsl · Oslo, 2021

metadata.description:
Capturing clouds... an old dream of mad scientist... coming true...
But wait... are they real clouds ? Maybe... maybe not...
Is it the real life ?
Is this just fantasy ?

Key 's'  : Save an image of the output at the current resolution
Key 1-9 : Change resolution
Key 'c' to change color palette

Features.
18 different features displayed (format, color palettes, main elements characteristics, rare elements...).

metadata.name: Disintegrating #138
metadata.description:
Disintegrating is an animated, interactive piece which allows the user to change the colour and luminosity of the lines within the artwork using mouse movement.

Move the mouse around the screen to see the colour changing effects.

mouseclick will stop the animation at its current state
'spacebar' will restart the animation
'r' will reset and restart the animation
'f' will set the animation to no disintegration at the current colours

Disintegrating is my first piece which includes a Webgl shader integrated with p5.js coding.
